## Goal
Build a multi-page luxury hotel booking web app that is simple, correct, and cleanly structured for an exam project + portfolio case study.

## Tech Stack (strict)
- HTML, CSS, Vanilla JavaScript, Bootstrap 5 (CDN is OK)
- Vite (multi-page build, each page is its own HTML file)
- Supabase (DB + Auth + Storage). No other backend.
- NO TypeScript. NO React/Vue. NO heavy libraries.

## Pages (each in src/pages/)
- index.html (home)
- hotels.html (hotel cards)
- destinations.html (destination cards)
- adventures.html (blog-like cards)
- booking.html (create booking + file upload)
- users.html (my bookings / profile)
- admin.html (admin-only management)
- login.html / register.html

## Architecture Rules
- Keep code modular and small:
  - src/js/services/* = all Supabase queries (no DOM code here)
  - src/js/auth/* = auth logic + route guards
  - src/js/ui/* = reusable UI rendering helpers (navbar, toasts, card rendering)
  - Page scripts only: DOM + event listeners + call services
- Avoid monolithic files. Prefer multiple small modules.
- Use async/await and basic try/catch error handling.

## Supabase Data Model (minimum)
Tables:
- profiles (id uuid PK -> auth.users)
- hotels (id, name, destination_id, description, cover_image_path)
- destinations (id, name, country, description, cover_image_path)
- bookings (id, user_id, hotel_id, start_date, end_date, guests, note, status, attachment_path)
- adventures (id, author_id, hotel_id nullable, title, content, cover_image_path, created_at)
- user_roles (user_id unique, role = 'admin' or 'user')

Storage:
- bucket: uploads (hotel images and/or booking attachments)

## Security (must)
- Use Supabase Auth (register/login/logout).
- Assume Row Level Security (RLS) is enabled and enforce permissions server-side.
- Policies:
  - hotels/destinations/adventures: public read; admin-only write
  - bookings: user can CRUD only own; admin can access all; status changes only by admin
  - roles: only admin can manage roles
- Never rely only on client-side checks for permissions.

## UI Requirements
- Responsive layout (mobile + desktop) with Bootstrap grid.
- Use simple luxury styling (spacing, typography, card layouts).
- Keep UI consistent via shared navbar component injected on each page.

## Development Workflow (important)
- Implement in small steps: prompt -> code -> run -> test -> refine
- Make frequent commits with clear messages (feat/fix/chore/docs).
- Keep database changes as SQL migrations in supabase/migrations and commit them.

## Output Expectations
When generating code:
- Provide file-by-file changes.
- Prefer simple, readable solutions.
- Do not introduce features beyond the requested scope.